\f1\b0\fs22 \cf0 No hope. No release. No end.\
A Crapsack World is a horrible setting where the {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://tvtropes.org/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/TheCynic"}}{\fldrslt \cf2 jaded}} notion of \'93{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://tvtropes.org/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/FinaglesLaw"}}{\fldrslt \cf2 anything that can go wrong}} will go 
\f2\i horribly
\f1\i0  wrong\'94 almost always applies, and it corrupts its inhabitants into {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://tvtropes.org/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/HumansAreBastards"}}{\fldrslt \cf2 perpetuating that nastiness against each other}}. More succinctly, trying to survive in one of these places {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://tvtropes.org/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/ThisIsGonnaSuck"}}{\fldrslt \cf2 is gonna suck}}.\
Although there are countless ways Crapsack Worlds can be depicted (often with {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://tvtropes.org/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/SceneryGorn"}}{\fldrslt \cf2 Scenery Gorn}}), it is usually {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://tvtropes.org/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/DarkerAndEdgier"}}{\fldrslt \cf2 dark}}, and on the {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://tvtropes.org/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/CynicismTropes"}}{\fldrslt \cf2 cynical end}} of the {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://tvtropes.org/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/SlidingScaleOfIdealismVsCynicism"}}{\fldrslt \cf2 Sliding Scale of Idealism vs.\'a0Cynicism}}, so it will have either {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://tvtropes.org/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/GreyAndGrayMorality"}}{\fldrslt \cf2 Grey and Gray Morality}} or {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://tvtropes.org/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/BlackAndGrayMorality"}}{\fldrslt \cf2 Black and Gray Morality}}, if not outright {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://tvtropes.org/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/EvilVersusEvil"}}{\fldrslt \cf2 Evil vs.\'a0Evil}} in the worst of cases (beware of {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://tvtropes.org/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/DarknessInducedAudienceApathy"}}{\fldrslt \cf2 Darkness-Induced Audience Apathy}} if you decide to go this route though). Settings like these are not kind at all to {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://tvtropes.org/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/WideEyedIdealist"}}{\fldrslt \cf2 idealists}}, who usually get {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://tvtropes.org/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/BreakTheCutie"}}{\fldrslt \cf2 traumatized}} and/or {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://tvtropes.org/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/CruelAndUnusualDeath"}}{\fldrslt \cf2 die horribly}} when their attempts to change the world through idealism meet tragic ends.\
Heroes in this setting are usually {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://tvtropes.org/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/AntiHero"}}{\fldrslt \cf2 Anti Heroes}}, and often have at least a bit of the {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://tvtropes.org/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/DeadpanSnarker"}}{\fldrslt \cf2 Deadpan Snarker}} about them. {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://tvtropes.org/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/BeingGoodSucks"}}{\fldrslt \cf2 Being good will suck}}, and if there are genuinely good heroes in this setting, expect them to be {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://tvtropes.org/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/KnightInSourArmor"}}{\fldrslt \cf2 Knights In Sour Armor}} and/or {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://tvtropes.org/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/HurtingHero"}}{\fldrslt \cf2 Hurting Heroes}}\'97more idealistic heroes such as the {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://tvtropes.org/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/KnightInShiningArmor"}}{\fldrslt \cf2 Knight in Shining Armor}} tend to not last long in this kind of setting. Any victories they manage to win over the forces of this world are likely to be {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://tvtropes.org/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/PyrrhicVictory"}}{\fldrslt \cf2 Pyrrhic}} in nature.\
Villains tend to run the gamut from sympathetic {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://tvtropes.org/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/AntiVillain"}}{\fldrslt \cf2 Anti Villains}} (on any level of the {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://tvtropes.org/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/SlidingScaleOfAntiVillains"}}{\fldrslt \cf2 Sliding Scale of Anti-Villains}}) right down to the most horrific monsters to grace any kind of media. Truly awful villains are especially common in these kinds of settings, both to represent the misery of the setting in general and to give the {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://tvtropes.org/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/AntiHero"}}{\fldrslt \cf2 Anti-Hero}} someone to whom he can look good in comparison. In truly extreme cases, even the most {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://tvtropes.org/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/VillainWithGoodPublicity"}}{\fldrslt \cf2 popular}} or powerful of these monsters {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://tvtropes.org/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/BeingEvilSucks"}}{\fldrslt \cf2 suffer just as badly as everyone else}}. And {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://tvtropes.org/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/AnyoneCanDie"}}{\fldrslt \cf2 Anyone Can Die}}.\
From here, these worlds can be depicted by authors in various ways, whether it would be dramatic or comedic, immutable or mutable. Though most of the time immutable equals dramatic, it is possible to see combinations between these categories.\
